author: akutz
message:
Add new flags to generate-yaml

This patch adds new flags to the generate-yaml script.

* -c can be used to specify the name of the cluster
* -m is used to specify the name of the CAPV manager image

If -c is specified then the output directory becomes
"./out/CLUSTER_NAME". If -o OUT_DIR is specified then the output
directory is "OUT_DIR". Use -o to specify explicit output directories,
otherwise the directories are unique based on the name of the cluster.

Fix datastore selection based on storagepolicy

When storage policy is specified, CAPV will fetch compatible datastores
and randomly selects one, however the return set also contains
datastore cluster. This will leads to long-time retries and even clone
failures.

message:
Delete node explicitly upon deletion of vm

This patch adds the logic to delete the k8s node from the cluster
corresponding to the VM. This is necessary in cases where the node is
never in the Ready state which leads to the node never getting removed
from the cluster. This leads to a lot of stale nodes showing on the
cluster with an active MHC.

author: srm09
message:
Drops version check when tracking owners

During the VM reconciliation, the controllers track down the parent of
the Machine objects using the owner reference hierarchy. The owner
reference checks were comparing the Group as well as the API version to
determins and fetch the owner.

Currently, the API version used for comparison was selected from the
storageVersion of the CAPI objects on the API server. Due to this, any
objects created via an earlier CAPI version, say v1alpha3, which sets
the owner reference API version to group name + v1alpha3 were not being
found since no such object would exist. A similar object with the
updated API type is stored in the api server.

This drify happens since CAPI does not update the owner references of
the objects when moving to newer API versions. There is an issue
tracking this https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/issues/7224
which will solve the stale owner ref API version problem. Until then we
are dropping the version check and just relying on the group info and
kind combination to fetch the parent object.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: srm09
message:
Introduces parameter for CP zone selection

This patch introduces a new parameter for selecting zones for control
plane nodes.
In the past, all zones having the same vCenter URL in the
spec.server would be associated to a vSphereCluster object with the same
vCenter URL set in the spec.server.
Now the vSphereCluster spec exposes a label based selection which can be
used to choose the zones for control plane node placement. The label
selector follows the same rules as described on the label selector types in
https://pkg.go.dev/k8s.io/apimachinery@v0.26.1/pkg/apis/meta/v1#LabelSelector

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: johananl
message:
Don't hardcode kube-vip interface

Hardcoding eth0 breaks environments where interface names other than
eth0 are used.

kube-vip supports interface autodetection as of v0.4.0.

Reintroduce the VIP_NETWORK_INTERFACE env var with a default of an
empty string. This way, the default behavior is autodetection while
the user can still explicitly specify an interface.

Signed-off-by: Johanan Liebermann <jliebermann@microsoft.com>

author: srm09
message:
Reorders the PCI device attachment process

This patch reorders the process of attaching PCI devices to the VM.
Previously, the PCI devices were attached during the VM cloning
operation, but the PCI device attachment requires a minimum hardware
version of vmx-17.
Instead of forcing the template to be hardcoded with a minimum hardware
version, CAPV introduced the capability of upgrading the hardware
version of the VM post clone operation succeeds. This would mean that
the PCI devices need to be attached after the upgrade hardware VM task
is finished and the hardware version of the VM has been successfully
upgraded to some compatible version specified by the user.

author: stmcginnis
message:
Update golangci-lint to 1.43.0

This updates the version of golangcli-lint we are using to 1.43.0. This
version picks up linter releases that address issues when running under
go 1.17. This prepares us for eventually raising the required golang
version for the project and makes sure developers that have newer
versions installed can run local tests without issues.

The newer versoin of golangci-lint brings with it additional checks that
were not enforced before. Due to that, in addition to raising the
golangci-lint version this also fixes a lot of (most minor) things that
the newer version uncovered.

This touchs a very large number of files. In almost all cases though,
the changes in these files are very minor cosmetic updates.

Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <smcginnis@vmware.com>

author: sidharthsurana
message:
Start using the new machinespec definition for creating the instance on vsphere (#72)

The code now acts accordingly based on the availability of the new cloud-init datasource
"VMwareGuestInfo" inside the template used. This availability can be set by the users in
the spec using the flag "vsphereCloudInit" set to true. For usual upstream version of
ubuntu cloud image that has been used so far, this flag need not be set at all and the
controller will utilize the OVF properties available on the ubuntu cloud image to inject
the cloud-init data.
Note: The new static IP support is only available with the templates that have the vsphere
cloud-init datasource. DHCP based IPs will continue to work as they have in the past.

Going forward we prefer users creating a custom ubuntu cloud image that also has this new
cloud-init datasource pre-installed. As that will give them the ability to use static IPs
as well if they want.

See https://github.com/akutz/cloud-init-vmware-guestinfo for more info on the new cloud-init
datasource

* Adds support for multiple nics
* Adds support for static IP

Resolves #24
Resolves #28

Change-Id: Id2dee12b382d57b6591f840dadd77a1c287667c4

author: srm09
message:
Multi AZ bug fixes

1. VSphere DRS enforces host placement according to affinity rules
   before powering on the VM. Since, the VM was being added after being
   powered on, the host placement wasn't being enforced.
   Add the VM to the VM group before powering it on, makes sure that
   the placement constraint is enforced.
2. Instead of re-creating the same category with a new associable type
   (which is not supported by Vsphere), we are now patching the category
   to update the associable type for a category.
3. Updating the failure domain on the VSphereMachine is not allowed,
   hence removed it.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

This patch introduces a new annotation "capv.sigs.k8s.io/maintenance"
that currenly anyone can put on the Machine object to instruct the
actuator to skip any kind of reconciliation on the machine object.

This can be used for various situations like(only sample use cases):
- admin wants to perform maintenance on the underlying infra for which
  they might need to power down VMs
- create bulk machine objects without the actuator creating them all at once,
  but only have them realized as needed by removing this annotation

Change-Id: I5a22c7abbe819f34a05c482c19d8625a661eaeaf

message:
Make the install and configure part of the scripts match the intent (#124)

Currently the configure part of the init script is also installing
packages, which should not be the case. The install part of the script
should be installing anything needed during the configure part.
This split is further used when we want to use template that is
pre-loaded with all the binaries. In that case, we only want to run
the configure part which would bring up the services

author: gab-satchi
message:
Implement support for supervisor based vsphereClusters
- adds branch to main.go start different controllers based on CRDs loaded
- creates vsphereCluster and vsphereClusterSupervisor reconcilers
- adds services required for supervisor based vsphereclusters
- Implement support for supervisor based vsphereMachines
- interface defined for VSphereMachine service which will be used by reconciler. reconcileNormal calls out to VSphereMachineService to reconcile the machine.
- moved vspheremachine_unit tests for failureDomain under VIMMachineService test
- baseMachineContext that will be shared by the two specialized vsphereMachine contexts
- adds vmoperator machine service capable of reconciling a vmOperator VirtualMachine given a VSphereMachine
- using untagged vm-operator-api to make use of conditions
- use modules from vm-operator for ncp and topology types
- network provider provided via a flag
- VSphereMachines can now be deleted even if cluster/vsphereCluster isn't found
- CAPI machine is a requirement to delete VSphereMachines
- abstract fetching VSphereClusters and VSphereMachines behind the VMService interface

author: aartij17
message:
Fixes secret fetch logic for vmware controllers

The provider service account and service discovery controllers had an
inherent assumption that the names of the Cluster and VSphereCluster
object is the same. Hence the logic to fetch the secret containing the
kubeconfig of the guest cluster was leveraging the name of the
VSphereCluster object.
With the advent of ClusterClass, the name of the generated
VSphereCluster object is different than the name of the Cluster object.

This patch adds the logic to get the owner Cluster object from the
VSphereCluster object and use that to generate the name of the secret
that contains the kubeconfig.
It also updates the test logic by passing different name to the Cluster
object.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: sidharthsurana
message:
Overload the VMTemplate parameter for search purposes

The MachineSpec.VMTemplate currently is treated as name of
the VM to be searched. In certain cases the name of the VM
can be duplicated inside a VC, thus we need a more precise
mechanism to point to a VM to be used as a template. For
this purpose we are now allowing the VMTemplate to also
be a valid UUID that would then be matched with the VMs
InstanceUUID property which is guaranteed to be unique.

The modified logic detects if the passed string looks like
a valid UUID then it tried to find the VM by InstaceUUID
if not found, then it fall back on treating the string as
the VM name.

Resolves #109

Change-Id: Ia5e6ca600a71ca784b54336299818b6ec892b949

author: adobley
message:
reconcile IPAddressClaims earlier

IPAddressClaims must be fulfilled before a VM can be powered on. This
could take some time depending on the IPAM Provider. By creating these
claims first we can give the provider time to fulfill these while the VM
is cloning, reducing the overall wait time for a VM to be ready.

Signed-off-by: Aidan Obley <aobley@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Edwin Xie <exie@vmware.com>

author: srm09
message:
Support new control plane taint

In k8s 1.24, kubeadm adds the label
`node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane` to the control plane nodes. To
deploy CAPV to 1.24 k8s clusters, the toleration needs to be added to
the CAPV deployment to support running the controllers on 1.24 control
plane nodes.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: akutz
message:
Update ready-state logic

This patch updates the ready-state logic for the Cluster and Machine
objects. A machine is not marked as ready until it is possible to
connect to the target cluster and verify the machine is represented
there as a node.

Additionally, this patch relocates the code to create the KubeConfig
secret from the Cluster's Reconcile function to the Machine's Update
function. This is because the KubeConfig secret must be created before a
Cluster can verify its ready state. If the Cluster didn't create the
KubeConfig until after it was ready, then a circular dependency would be
created, and a Cluster would never appear as ready.

Finally, several existing calls have been changed to rely on the CAPI
NodeRef/Remote packages in order to get a client for a target cluster
or retrieve a KubeConfig for the target cluster.

author: srm09
message:
Creates token secret for service account

This patch changes the default behavior of waiting for the generation of
a default secret for the service account and propagate that over to the
guest cluster.
Instead, alongwith the service account a secret of type
"kubernetes.io/service-account-token" is created to host the token for
the service account. The controller waits for the realization of this
secret and then propagates this data over to the guest cluster.

This is required since 1.24 disables the auto generation of a default
token secret for every service account created.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: akutz
message:
Support for kubeadm bootstrapping & using new imgs

This patch adds support for using kubeadm for bootstrapping onto the new
CAPV images. This is to align CAPV's features with those in CAPA.

Add unit test for GetMachineRole

This patch adds a unit test for GetMachineRole.

Updated CAPI to same version as CAPA

This patch updates the CAPI dependency to the same version used by CAPA.

Update CI provider component logging

This patch sets the log level in the CI provider components file to 6.

Remove unused code in GoVmomi utils

This patch removes unused code in GoVmomit utils.

Centralize API updates

This patch removes the code that updated the taskref from inside the
GoVmomi create callstack. The machines are now only updated as part of a
deferred routine in the actuators.

Return if find VM by moref

This patch returns from the Create call if the VM is found by its MoRef.

Refactored to use Cluster & Machine Contexts

Akin to CAPA's Scopes, this patch introduces support for Cluster &
Machine contexts, making writing code much, much easier, as well as
centralizing all of the boilerplate work that happens at the beginning
and end of each request into the context.

Initialize loggers with actuator IDs

This patch ensures the cluster and machine actuator loggers have the
correct prefix.

Lock the klog library to v0.2.0

Updating the project with support for klogr caused the klog dependency
to be updated to v0.3.1, and that was causing CI to break.

Support disabling validation on gen yaml

This patch adds support for disabling the validation of certain env vars
when generating yaml with generate-yaml.sh

Use CAPI 0.1.3 image

This patch switches to using the CAPI 0.1.3 image due to an error
starting CAPI inside of Kind with the 0.1.2 image. Please see
https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/issues/999 for more
information.

Refactored Actuators, removed informers

This patch refactors the actuators into discreet packages and removed
the use of informers. This patch also relocates the setup code for the
controller into the manager binary's main file.

Update e2e kubectl bin to 1.14.2

This patch updates the kubectl binary used by the e2e job to 1.14.2.

Add SSH auth keys to cloud-init

This patch forwards the ClusterConfig's SSH auth keys list into the
cloud-init data.

Allow a machine to return control plane endpoint

This patch allows a machine to return a control plane endpoint to
satisfy the ProviderDeployer interface. Please see the Slack
conversation
https://kubernetes.slack.com/archives/C8TSNPY4T/p1560696064368600 for
more information.

author: akutz
message:
Enhanced networking support

This patch adds support for enhanced network configuration:

* Multiple devices
* Multiple address per device
* Multiple address families per device
* Multiple gateways of multiple address families
* Global, static routes
* Per-device, static routes

To achieve this required refactoring the reconciliation logic in order
to separate the creation of VMs from when they are booted. All of this
is tied to the new Exists workflow, documented in the docs folder as a
diagram. This is key to understanding how CAPV works.

author: adobley
message:
prevent IPAM addresses from being assigned to multiple devices

we had previously made an assumption that the
VSphereVM.Spec.Network.Devices[*].MACAddr would be set. This caused us
to generate IPAMState that could be keyed on an empty string and later
read for every device without a MACAddr set.

we now rely on the NetworkStatus as the source of truth for MACAddr to
key and later retrieve the correct IPAM configuration for devices.

Signed-off-by: Aidan Obley <aobley@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Edwin Xie <exie@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Tyler Schultz <tschultz@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Christian Ang <angc@vmware.com>

author: akutz
message:
Use CloudInit bootstrap w VM Operator

This patch updates CAPV to use the VM Operator CloudInit
bootstrap method instead of ExtraConfig. This change
ensures there is no race between VM Tools and CloudInit
since using ExtraConfig will cause Guest OS Customization
to configure the network, resulting in a reboot while
CloudInit is running. Specifying CloudInit as the bootstrap
provider ensures VM Operator uses CloudInit to bootstrap the
network.

Please note this patch will only work in vSphere 7P05+.

author: johananl
message:
flatcar: Run kubeadm after containerd

Ensure kubeadm runs after containerd to avoid a race condition between
the two.

We intentionally add an After= directive and not a Requires= directive
to avoid breaking things for distros which use Ignition and don't use
containerd.

See https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/image-builder/issues/939.

Signed-off-by: Johanan Liebermann <jliebermann@microsoft.com>

message:
Customizable sync period

This patch introduces support for customizing the CAPV manager's sync
period via the environment variable "SYNC_PERIOD" and/or the CLI flag
"--sync-period". If set, the environment variable modifies the default
value for the flag, otherwise the default sync period is 10 minutes.

provision new VMs on vSphere, and the VSphereMachine controller has been
refactored to use this method. The reason for this change is to support
deploying the HAProxy load balancer OVA using the existing GoVmomi
infrastructure in place to deploy the k/k machine images.

author: dougm
message:
Only set PVC zone annotation when zonal storage classes are required

The CSI zone annotation must be set when using a zonal storage class,
which is required when the cluster has multiple (3) zones.
Single zone clusters (legacy/default) do not support zonal storage and must not
have the zone annotation set.

See also: #1573

author: srm09
message:
Handles error for node controller

During B/R operations, the cluster owner ref is somethimes not present
immediately. This might throw an error which when unhandled causes the
controller to crash.
This patch handles the error case and requeues the reconcile request for
a later time.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: srm09
message:
Updates RBAC permissions

This patch does the following two things:
- Adds an aggregration rule for the CAPV manager role which can be used
  to add permissions to the manager role on the fly. External clients
  such as addons providers for CPI/CSI can use this label to add
  permissions to the manager dynamically, thereby reducing the need to
  hardcode these permissions in CAPV.
- It also cleans up the patch files to add the CAPI and KCP aggregation
  labels to the CAPV manager role

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: sidharthsurana
message:
Fix the kubelet config for version 1.11 and above (#68)

The systemd unit definition of the kubelet sources the file
/etc/default/kubelet for any env variables. The default file
generated for /etc/default/kubelet has an empty value like
`KUBELET_EXTRA_ARGS=`. This causes the kubelet to not use the
actual value of KUBELET_EXTRA_ARGS set in the override file
/etc/systemd/system/kubelet.service.d/20-cloud.conf

author: akutz
message:
Build HAProxy OVA with Photon 3 Rev2 minimal

This patch uses the Photon 3 Rev2 minimal ISO to build the HAProxy OVA.
This reduces the size of the ISO downloaded to build the OVA from +5GiB
to ~300MiB.

One aspect of this patch requires installing additional packages in the
post-install script in the kickstart. While the additional_packages
element is still present, its list of packages is installed with tdnf in
the script at the bottom of the kickstart file. This is because the
Photon minimal ISO consults only itself when processing the
additional_packages directive, and any package not found on the minimal
ISO, including "sudo", will not be installed.

author: mcwumbly
message:
Fix VSphereCluster VCenterAvailable condition

We now check the connectivity regardless of whether
CloudProviderConfiguration is set on the spec.

That property has been deprecated and it is valuable to check this
connectivity early and surface this on the VSphereCluster status rather
than just on VSphereVMs.

This also fixes a bug where the status could be set to "False" if the
secret was not found and then never properly set to "True" once the secret
becomes present.

https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/issues/1209

Co-authored-by: Guangyuan Wang <wguangyuan@vmware.com>

author: akutz
message:
Cloud provider credentials as secret

This patch changes the way the cloud provider obtains its credential
information. Instead of directly via the cloud config file, a Kubernetes
Secret object is created on target clusters that is used by the cloud
provider. This is a much more secure design as credentials are no longer
transported via the GuestInfo RPC mechanism as base64-encoded plain-text
data.

author: akutz

author: srm09
message:
Adds logic to reconcile cluster modules

This patch exposes the logic which creates/deletes a cluster module
construct for every cluster-api object responsible for creating new
Machine/VSphereVM/K8s node objects. For each such object, CAPV creates a
cluster module which best effort guarantees anti affinity placement of
VMs belonging to this CAPI object on the ESXi hosts.

This patch introduces a new feature flag which gates the anti affinity
functionality.
The name of the feature flag is `NodeAntiAffinity` and can be set/reset by
setting the `EXP_NODE_ANTI_AFFINITY` to true/false.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: mrajashree
message:
Enqueue VSphereMachine in clusterToVSphereMachines mapper

The clusterToVSphereMachines mapper gets a list of machines in a cluster
and enqueues objects using the Machine's name instead of the corresponding
VSphereMachine's name. If the VSphereMachine and Machine object are named differently,
the controller can't reconcile the VSphereMachine object since it tries
to find it by the wrong name. This commit changes the mapper to enqueue
the corresponding VSphereMachine of a Machine by using InfrastructureRef.Name
field

author: srm09
message:
Adds logic for deletion of orphaned VSphereMachine

This patch adds the logic for the deletion of orphaned vspheremachine
objects. Orphaned VSphereMachine objects are those who do not have the
CAPI Machine objects set as their owners. This situation could arise if
the owner CAPI Machine gets deleted before claiming the VSphereMachine
object as its dependent object.
There is a CAPI bug which is supposed to solve this issue, but in the
meanwhile, if the VSPhereMachine does not have any other owner
references apart from the VSphereCluster object, then we delete those
objects during VSphereCluster deletion loop.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

author: srm09
message:
Fix vCenter session leaks

On controller startup, the reconciliation loops for the VSphereCluster
and VSphereVM objects make a call to the seesion.GetOrCreate function
to look for existing sessions. Without the mutex guarding the access to
the function, all the objects end up creating a session, and the last
created session which gets saved in the cache gets used for future API
calls and the other sessions are left to idle.
Also, altered the logout logic to destroy the session using the govmomi
method calls directly.

Another improvement made here was to destroy the sessions on managaer
shutdown so that CAPV does not leave over any sessions on manager exit.

author: srm09
message:
Updates disk size for clone test

The PR https://github.com/vmware/govmomi/pull/2911 introduces a
validation which does not allow disk resize operations to lower the size
of the disk. After the govmomi dependency update, the current setup of
the clone test setup was resizing the disk to a smaller value. Hence the
test setup had to be updated to update the disk size from 10GB to 20GB.

author: akutz
message:
Shell with GOPATH

This patch updates the Makefile to use a custom shell based on
"hack/shell-with-gopath.sh" to ensure that even when building outside
the GOPATH, K8s tooling will still work.

This patch also:

* Updates any go:generate code to use scripts in "hack/" since
go:generate ignores the current, working directory
* Removes the Makefile from "config/crds" and puts that logic into
"hack/update-generated.sh" since recursive Make does not use the custom
shell
* Remove the CRD validation added in
50dc7f0264761df87288f5aeea883c52401521f1. This will be replaced with a
new Prow pre-submit test that will call "hack/verify-crds.sh"

This patch fixes the one caveat with the approach of a nested GOPATH,
which was that if it was created in or out of a container, either the
host or the container wouldn't work the next time "make" was invoked.
This corrects that by checking first to see if the symlink is broken and
recreating it if it is.

author: sidharthsurana
message:
Fix the kubelet config for version 1.11 and above for worker nodes (#88)

The systemd unit definition of the kubelet sources the file
/etc/default/kubelet for any env variables. The default file
generated for /etc/default/kubelet has an empty value like
`KUBELET_EXTRA_ARGS=`. This causes the kubelet to not use the
actual value of KUBELET_EXTRA_ARGS set in the override file
/etc/systemd/system/kubelet.service.d/20-cloud.conf

This is the same fix as PR#68 which fixed this issue with master
node. This PR expands the same fix to worker nodes as well

The root issue is without this the kubelet on the node starts
without the `--cloud-provider=vsphere` flag causing the node to
be not recognized as a cloud instance

Change-Id: Ia73dc7e86ca193b42cea3ac7dc7cc22bebcd7ab4

author: adobley
message:
Add implementation of Node IPAM support

- Adds `addressesFromPools` to the VSphereVM network device spec
- Creates IPAddressClaims when AddressesFromPools is specified
- IP addresses created by IPAM providers are assigned to vSphere
  machines via the VM metadata
- IPv4 Gateways from IPAddresses (created by IPAM providers) are
  assigned to the Gateway4 field
- IPv6 Gateways from IPAddresses (created by IPAM providers) are assigned
  to the Gateway6 field
- All gateways in the same IP family assigned to a VSphereVM network
  device must be the same.
- This implementation expects that an appropriate gateway for the IP
  family exists for every IPAddress that comes from an IPAM provider.
- Adds the `IPAddressClaimed` Condition to provide visibility of the
  status of IP address acquisition
- Adds the finalizer to prevent IPAMClaims from being deleted early
- IPAddressClaims have an OwnerReference to VSphereVMs to ensure they
  are garbage-collected when the VM is deleted.

Co-authored-by: Tyler Schultz <tschultz@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Christian Ang <angc@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Edwin Xie <exie@vmware.com>

author: codenrhoden
message:
Modify -ci image makefile to default to build only

When running `make` with no arguments in scripts/e2e/bootstrap_job, the
default behavior was to build the image, push the image to gcr.io, and
delete the local copy of the image. That's not a useful default.
Instead, change the "all" target to just have "build" as a pre-req,
making "make" the equivalent of "make build". If someone wants to push
images, they can run "make push" instead. Deleting the local image is an
explicit step left to "make clean".

author: akutz
message:
Reconcile based on task completion

This patch introduces the ability to trigger reconcile events for any
resource based on external events, such as when a task completes.

This patch removes the DefaultRequeue logic for the VSphereMachine
controller and replaces it by triggering a GenericEvent for a
VSphereMachine when an associated task for the VSphereMachine's back-end
VM completes (successfully or otherwise).

author: stmcginnis
message:
Make conversion-gen output location explicit

The conversion-gen command has an --output-base argument to control
where generated files are placed. The default value for this argument
can vary depending on whether or not $GOPATH is set or not. This results
in our generated files being created in the wrong place for some people
in a subtle and non-obvious way.

For those running `make generate` with GOPATH set, the files are created
in `$GOPATH/src/[file path]`. For those without GOPATH set, files are
created where we expect them to be within the repo at `./[file path]`.

To make sure files are always generated to the location where we expect
them to be, this updates our calls to conversion-gen to always be
explicit and set `--output-base=./`.

Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <smcginnis@vmware.com>

author: akutz
message:
Add script for building dev artifacts

This patch adds the script "hack/build-dev.sh" that:

* Builds the CAPV manager image from the local, working copy of CAPV
  and pushes the image to
  "gcr.io/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/dev/v1alpha2/capv-manager:latest"

* Builds the CAPV manifests image from the local, working copy of CAPV
  and pushes the image to
  "gcr.io/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/dev/v1alpha2/capv-manifests:latest"

* Builds the CAPI manager image from its upstream repository's "master"
  branch and pushes the image to to
  "gcr.io/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/dev/v1alpha2/capi-manager:latest"

* Builds the CABPK manager image from its upstream repository's "master"
  branch and pushes the image to to
  "gcr.io/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/dev/v1alpha2/cabpk-manager:latest"

Move IPAddressClaim reconcile to controller

the vsphereVM controller.
It also:

  Introduces a watcher on the IPAddressClaim object to enqueue a reconcile
  request for the VSphereVM owner object.
- Reorders Ready condition calculation logic:
  Re-orders the conditions used to geenrate the summary condition on the
  VSphereVM object.
- Adds new ipam sub-package under govmomi pkg:
  This resturctures the logic to check for the bound IP address claims and
  building the corresponding IPAM state which gets passed to the metadata
  reconcile method.

author: sidharthsurana
message:
Add a new MachineSpec for defining the instance on vsphere (#71)

* Move the MachineRef property into the ProviderConfig

* Move the `MachineRef` property from `ProviderStatus` to `ProviderConfig` object
* Upon creation of the `VirtualMachine` the `MachineRef` will be populated inside the spec
* Update the glog logs to use higher verbosity for improved readability of logs

Resolves #82

Change-Id: I4ef1c5dec11d0c06dd777daae6500f4fe6f13241

* Add a new machinespec for defining the instance on vsphere

With the new structure we should be able to:
* Support defining multiple nics
* Support providing dhcp/static IP configuration for each nic
* Support customizing multiple disks if present
* Adds a optional flag called "vsphereCloudInit" to indicate if
  the template used has the vsphere datasource for cloud-init
  present and enabled

Note: This change does not change the existing behavior of using
the MachineVariables string map. This will be handled in the
subsequent patches.

Partially Resolves #24
Partially Resolves #28

Change-Id: Ia49b8ef9984cf6b82f4885179491ac3b3cc6f369

author: akutz
message:
Reuse CAPI bootstrap secret with Supervisor

This patch removes the logic for creating a new ConfigMap
resource for Supervisor VMs. Instead CAPV simply points
the Supervisor resources to the existing CAPI bootstrap
secrets.

Previously Supervisor integration required setting
the ControlPlaneEndpoint value in Cloud-Init metadata.
However, this was recognized as vestigial as the
KubeadmBootstrap controller automatically grabs the
ControlPlaneEndpoint from the
Cluster.Spec.ControlPlaneEndpoint field if the value is
not explicitly specified.

For more information please see the following links:

* The CAPV Cluster reconciler does not proceed until there is a control plane endpoint -- https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/blob/cc735927f7c7671dc8f30bc796474fa62555a127/controllers/vmware/vspherecluster_reconciler.go#L184-L188
* The CAPV Cluster reconciler only marks the Cluster as "ready" when there is a valid control plane endpoint -- https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/blob/cc735927f7c7671dc8f30bc796474fa62555a127/controllers/vmware/vspherecluster_reconciler.go#L190
* The CAPI Core KubeadmBootstrap reconciler does not proceed unless the Cluster is marked as "ready" -- https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/blob/bc177c6906e8b7063520777c2d608b7297fd86b9/bootstrap/kubeadm/internal/controllers/kubeadmconfig_controller.go#L234-L238
* The CAPI Core KubeadmBootstrap reconciler uses the value of Cluster.Spec.ControlPlaneEndpoint if one is not provided explicitly -- https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/blob/ffee0a45cf823965d6e6d578d93eb3b6730ec734/bootstrap/kubeadm/internal/controllers/kubeadmconfig_controller.go#L925-L931
* The CAPV Machine reconciler does not proceed until the bootstrap data is ready -- https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-vsphere/blob/cc735927f7c7671dc8f30bc796474fa62555a127/controllers/vspheremachine_controller.go#L292-L302

author: akutz
message:
Support special spec/status fields for VM CRDs

This patch requires VM CRDs, ex. VSphereVM or others, to support the
following fields:

  * spec.biosUUID    - a string that contains the VM's BIOS UUID
  * status.ready     - a boolean flag indicating whether or not
                       the VM is ready
  * status.addresses - an array of strings that contains the VM's
                       IP addresses

message:
deprecate(flags): Factor out --enable-keep-alive flag

deprecate(flags): enable-keep-alive flag

The --enable-keep-alive flag is deprecated, since the functionality is now enabled by default.
IN subsequent commits the keep-alive feature's dependence on this flag will be factored out.

refactor: Decouple the keep-alive feature from the flag

With this commit, the deprecated keep-alive feature flag is functionally removed.
All functionality that previously relied on the flag's presence has been
refactored to work without the flag. The CLI flag is still present but marked
deprecated.

The deprecated `--enable-keep-alive` is removed from the controller-manager's
deployment manifest.

author: randomvariable
message:
flavorgen: Use local_hostname instead of FQDN for node name

K8s resources are limited to 63 characters, so to ensure nodes can
join, they should not include the complete FQDN and instead be
limited only to the local hostname.

Furthermore, this cleans up the /etc/hosts file, and standardises with
the union of Debian and RHEL family local hostnames.

We also finally move wholly to systemd to set the hostname.

Signed-off-by: Naadir Jeewa <jeewan@vmware.com>

author: srm09
message:
Fixes panic when creating VSphereVM

This fixes a panic that was caused because of a race condition between
the VSphere machine controller creating the VM which was causing another
reconcile event being requeued for the same object. The other reconcile
event was sometimes failing to find the created VSphereVM from the
earlier request and trying to create the same object and failing with an
already exists error.
Now, the VSphereMachine controller omits the create events for the
VSphereVM objects since the controller is the author of those objects
and should not be notified for the same event.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

Update the Cluster controller endpoint logic

This patch changes the way the Cluster controller handles API endpoints.
The controller's logic no longer searches for the oldest control plane
member, because the oldest control plane member may not be the member

control plane.

author: chrischdi
message:
add explicit securityContexts to the controller

This does not really change the configuration, it just makes it explicit and enforce
the defaults, except for the seccompPolicy which changes from Unconfined to RuntimeDefault.
Syscalls filtered by RuntimeDefault policy are 95% namespaced and require capabilities
(which we drop) in the first place, so no practical change there either.

This allows to be compatible to the restricted pod security admission profile.

This is a recommendation in the CAPI v1.3->1.4 upgrade guide.

author: srm09
message:
Checks for feature flag during VM reconciliation

Adds the check for the state of the anti affinity feature flag when
reconciling VM. When reconciling the VM, the cluster module info should
be looked up only when the NodeAntiAffinity feature flag is turned on.
This also solves the issue when the control plane provider is something
other than the KubeadmControlPlane, in which case we do not want to
allow checks for cluster module info.

Signed-off-by: Sagar Muchhal <muchhals@vmware.com>

e2e with a working version of upstream CAPI please do the following:

        export CAPI_IMAGE=gcr.io/k8s-staging-cluster-api/cluster-api-controller:v20200103-v0.2.5-497-gdbe789259

The above should work until upstream CAPI fixes things.

author: akutz
message:
Update YAML generation to use Python

This patch updates the way the YAML manifests are generated to no longer
rely on envsubst and instead use Python, a language installed by default
on macOS and nearly all Linux distros. The changes include:

* The generation script is now located at hack/generate-yaml.sh
* The file hack/envsubst.py handles what used to require the gettext
package
* The image hack/tools/kustomize/Dockerfile is a Google distroless image
with the Kustomize tool. This image is only 20MIB in size.
* The generation script defaults to using the Kustomize image over a
local binary, but "-k local" can be used to prefer the local binary if
desired
* The manifest templates have been updated to account for API type
changes

author: srm09
message:
Removes test related flags from binary

The binary was exposing flags used specifically by the tests which is
misleading since the functioanlity of the binary is not altered by those
flags.
Two main causes of the flags being exposed were:
1. ginkgo and gomega packages used in code required by the controllers
2. legacy code add flags to only run unit tests or integration tests.

This patch refactors the code to remove the flags from showing up on the
binary.
